** The first thing we did with our data was to remove obviously correlated predictor variables and called this dataset HomeData2, after this we ran backwards elim, forwards elim, and step-wise regression on the resulting data. All three gave us the same Cpvalue of 14.651 and ended with the same result.

Then we decided to create another model from HomeData2 predictor variables. We then saw that the vif of the predictor variables were not extremely high. We took out predictor variables that did not have a significant p-value, then reran the t-test with our new model, and continued this until all predictors had a significant p-value. We called this model HouseData4. We then ran step-wise regression, forwards elim, and backwards elim on this model. The Cpvalue given was 11.000 for all three, because this cp-value was smaller than the first model’s cp-value, we decided this model was the best and named it BasicModel. **

** All of the predictors in the model have a significant p-value.

None of the vif values of the individual predictors are extremely high, the highest being GroundSF with a vif of 2.72

The low vif values of the predictors tell us that no individual predictors have a standard error that is inflated by a high factor, therefore no predictor’s t-value and p-value were majorly affected by multicollinearity. **

r_student <- rstudent(BasicModel)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(BasicModel$residuals~BasicModel$fitted.values, main="Residuals vs Fitted Values", xlab="Fitted Values", ylab="Residuals")
abline(0,0)
plot(r_student ~ BasicModel$fitted.values,  main="Studentized vs Fitted Values", xlab="Fitted Values", ylab="Student t")
abline(0,0)
abline(2,0, lty=2)
abline(-2,0, lty=2)
abline(3,0, lty=3)
abline(-3,0, lty=3)
qqnorm(BasicModel$residuals)
qqline(BasicModel$residuals)
hist(BasicModel$residuals, breaks=12,main="Histogram of Residuals", xlab="Residuals")

In terms of zero disturbance term, the distribution of the error is centered at zero. In other words, points are randomly scattered above and below the line. This can be confirmed by Residuals vs Fitted Plot and the histogram of residuals.

The residual vs fitted plot also tells us about the constant variance, which is not the case for our model, since residuals respond to changes in fitted values. There is some pattern, as shown by curved shape of distribution. Therefore, we cannot assume homoskedasticity, yet this issue is expected to be addressed in a fancier model that will appear in the Part 3, through transformations and other relevant techniques.

When it comes to influential points, there seem some mild cases, in the context of this dataset. A couple of residuals are away from the center. In this model, we consider any case more than 3 in absolute value as outliers and the largest residual value in the studentized plot is 5.15 in its magnitude. However, we did not simply get rid of outliers, in that there are several cases, 11 in total, and no clear reason to exclude them

When it comes to normality, we could merely refer to the histogram of residuals to see if the normality is met. However, histogram might sometimes not be informative if the number of bins is set inappropriately, usually with the small sample size. For more circumvent inspection, use a normal quantile plot of the residuals.

The histogram of residuals indicates that residuals seems closely normally distributed, yet normal Q-Q plot displays a little right skewness in the distribution of residuals.

We will also address this issue by transformation, in the latter part of this assignment.

** PART 3 **

We decided to create two summary comparison variables on the basis of their meaning. We created one summary variable which encapsulated all the different types of bathrooms, multiplying the half baths by .5 to represent their reduced value. We created an additional summary variable which encapsulated all the different porch square footages. We reasoned that the combination of them was sensible, as they were effectively divided by category and we combined them to avoid their more categorical nature.

After plotting the model described above, we observed nonlinearity in both YearBuilt and YearRemodel. As the model appeared to curve upward approaching the present, we decided to change the variables to effective equivalents of age, and years since remodel. This we reasoned would be best described with an inverted transformation. Finally, the graph of Fireplaces did not appear to have any particular slope, and so we eliminated the variable from the model. Thus the model below was produced.

modelFancy = lm(Price~I(BasementFBath+BasementHBath*.5+FullBath+HalfBath*.5)+I(WoodDeckSF + OpenPorchSF + EnclosedPorchSF + ScreenPorchSF)+LotFrontage + LotArea + I(1/(2019-YearBuilt)) + I(1/(2019-YearRemodel)) + BasementSF + GroundSF + Bedroom + TotalRooms + GarageSF, data=HomeData)
summary(modelFancy)

** PART 4 **

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(BasicModel$residuals ~ BasicModel$fitted.values, main="Basic Model: Residuals vs Fitted Values", xlab="Fitted Values", ylab="Residuals")
abline(0,0)
qqnorm(BasicModel$residuals, main="Basic Model: Normal Q-Q Plot")
qqline(BasicModel$residuals)
plot(modelFancy$residuals ~ modelFancy$fitted.values, main="Fancy Model: Residuals vs Fitted Values", xlab="Fitted Values", ylab="Residuals")
abline(0,0)
qqnorm(modelFancy$residuals, main="Fancy Model: Normal Q-Q Plot")
qqline(modelFancy$residuals)

The above plots are residuals vs fitted plot and Q-Q plot, each from the basic model and the fancy model. There seem little changes or improvements in fit, just by visual inspection, but the actual distribution of residuals in the fancy model has less curvature with less residuals squared value.

hist(modelFancy$residuals, breaks=15, main="Fancy Model: Histogram of Residuals", xlab="Residuals")

Same as before, the distribution of the error is centered at zero. Points are randomly scattered above and below the line, as illustrated by the histogram and residual vs fitted plot.

There is still some pattern in the distribution of the reisudals, yet less curved pattern indicates there is a slight improvement in fit.

r_student_fancy <- rstudent(modelFancy)

plot(r_student_fancy ~ modelFancy$fitted.values,  main="Model Fancy: Studentized vs Fitted Values", xlab="Fitted Values", ylab="Student t")
abline(0,0)
abline(2,0, lty=2)
abline(-2,0, lty=2)
abline(3,0, lty=3)
abline(-3,0, lty=3)

Again, couple of residuals are away from the center.

Overall,residuals seem closely normally distributed, yet there persists a little right skewness in the distribution of residuals, even after transformation to the fancy model..
